[1] Case updates
- Wed 5 Jun 2019. Epidemiological situation report, DRC Ministry of Health
[in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://mailchi.mp/sante.gouv.cd/ebola_kivu_05juin19?e=f96cddba3b

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri dated 4 Jun 2019:
- since the beginning of the epidemic, the cumulative number of cases is 2025, with 1931 confirmed and 94 probable. In total, there were 1357 deaths (1263 confirmed and 94 probable) and 552 people cured;
- 295 suspected cases under investigation;
- 5 new confirmed cases, including 2 in Katwa, 1 in Kalunguta, 1 in Mabalako, and 1 in Mandima;
- 3 new deaths of confirmed cases, including 2 community deaths -- 1 in Katwa and 1 in Kalunguta -- and 1 death at the Mabalako ETC;
- 10 new recoveries released from ETCs: 8 in Katwa and 2 in Butembo.

News
- The minister of health undertook a 2-day mission to Goma, Beni, and Aloya (Mabalako). Mabalako, which was the epicenter of the epidemic in August 2018, is facing a new outbreak concentrated in the health area of Aloya. Nearly 1/3 of new confirmed cases recorded in the last 21 days come from this area, making Mabalako the 1st hot spot of the outbreak, followed by Butembo and Katwa.
- During the minister of health's visit to Aloya, a popular assembly was held in the city center with a delegation of customary chiefs. The population was very receptive to the awareness messages and committed to ending Ebola at home as soon as possible.

Figures of the response
-----------------------
- 130 254 vaccinated persons
- 215 people vaccinated on 4 Jun 2019;
- of those vaccinated, 35 952 are high-risk contacts (HRC), 64 286 are contacts of contacts (CC), and 30 016 are front-line providers (FLP);
- persons vaccinated by health zone: 33 443 in Katwa, 25,719 in Beni, 17 536 in Butembo, 11 179 in Mabalako [total number of people vaccinated can be seen at the source URL above];
- 63 542 280 people under control;
- 80 entry points (PoE) and operational health checkpoints (OHC);
- 110 contaminated health workers;
- the cumulative number of confirmed/probable cases among health workers is 110 (5.4% of all confirmed/probable cases) including 37 deaths.

