[Helen Branswell (https://twitter.com/HelenBranswell)
So today is a rare (lately) day with only a handful of #Ebola cases. I'm not sure I trust this figure though. I hear things at Beni are still tense after the violence earlier this week; if response workers are restricting their movements, surveillance would be affected. 1/
3. Health minister @OlyIlunga was in Mabalako today urging the community to work to contain the #Ebola outbreak. Mabalako was the original hotspot for the outbreak last August [2018] & has seen the most transmission in the past 3 weeks of any of the transmission centers.
4. The weekly #Ebola report from @WHOAFRO is out. It notes there've been some good metrics in the past week or two. Fewer cases (though still lots!). More patients coming from contact lists, a sign surveillance is doing a better job tracking the virus. Less spread in hospitals.
5. But problems remain. The average time from detection of an #Ebola case to isolation in a treatment center (to prevent them from spreading the virus) is 6 days. And that's for cases detected before death. Too long. Delays in detection = delays in finding, vaccinating contacts.

[there is a notable absence in reports of cases from Beni over the past few days, most likely related to the current instable situation following another attack on the part of insurgents in the area. - Mod.MPP]

