- Mon 3 Jun 2019. Epidemiological situation report, DRC Ministry of Health
[in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=307c1f0c6f

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri dated 2 Jun 2019:
- since the beginning of the epidemic, the accumulated cases are 2008, including 1914 confirmed and 94 probable. In total, there were 1346 deaths (1252 confirmed and 94 probable) and 539 people cured;
- 281 suspected cases under investigation;
- 14 newly confirmed cases including 7 in Mabalako, 3 in Butembo, 2 in Katwa, 1 in Mandima, and 1 in Kalunguta;
- 7 new deaths of confirmed cases: 6 community deaths -- 4 in Mabalako, 1 in Katwa and 1 in Butembo -- and 1 death at the Butembo ETC;
- 6 new releases from ETCs -- 3 in Mabalako, 2 in Butembo, and 1 in Beni.

News
Evolution of the Ebola epidemic
-------------------------------
- The bar of the 2000 cases was passed Sun 2 Jun 2019. Despite this milestone, the developments of recent weeks are positive although we must remain vigilant.

Among the positive developments:
- Slight improvement in the security situation: the last attack against military teams and operations of the response against Ebola, which cost the life of Dr Richard Valery Mouzoko Kiboung, dates back more than a month. Although threats against the response remain high, the decrease in the number of targeted attacks allowed the teams to make up some of their tardiness to contain the spread of the epidemic. However, the security situation remains volatile and unpredictable. With respect to incidents of reluctance or community resistance, the majority of these incidents are resolved through the involvement of community leaders, sensitizers, and psychosocial experts.
- Geographical containment of the epidemic: despite the difficulties of response teams to do their work because of the security situation, the epidemic continues to be geographically contained, protecting the rest of the country and neighboring countries. To date, no cases of Ebola have crossed the borders of the Democratic Republic of Congo, and the epidemic has not spread in large, highest-risk urban centers, namely Goma, Bunia, and Kisangani. However, the risk remains high given the significant population movements. Moreover, since the beginning of the epidemic, 188 health areas in 22 health zones, through the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri, reported at least one case of Ebola. As of 2 Jun 2019, 9 health zones, including 106 health areas (56% of total), spent more than 21 days without notifying new confirmed cases. The 9 health zones concerned are Kyondo, Oicha, Kayna, Mutwanga [North Kivu], Komanda, Bunia, Rwampara, Nyankunde, and Tchomia [Ituri].

The main challenges to be addressed to end this epidemic are:
- Epidemiological surveillance: in order to break the chain of transmission, all contacts of confirmed cases must be listed and followed for 21 days. Now, among the 911 new confirmed cases recorded between [1 Jan and 7 May 2019], only 398 (44%) were registered as regular contacts. Thus, we must strengthen the listing and tracking of contacts involving more community authorities and leaders.
- Prevention and infection control (PCI): the prevention and control of infections should be strengthened in community health facilities to reduce the rate of nosocomial infection. Between 25% and 30% of infections occur in health facilities.
- Community death: the rate of community deaths remains high. Between 28% and 43% of deaths reported every week take place outside of an Ebola treatment center or a transit center. These deaths occur either in private hospitals and clinics, in community health centers, or at home. However, with the contagiousness of a patient being maximum after his death, funerals worthy and secure are possible to limit community spread. What is positive is that the majority of community deaths benefit from a secure and dignified burial.
- A complete analysis of the evolution of the epidemic of Ebola is available in a scientific article:
Ilunga Kalenga O, Moeti M, Sparrow A, Nguyen VK, Lucey D, Ghebreyesus TA; The ongoing Ebola epidemic in the Democratic Republic of Congo, 2018-2019. N Engl J Med. 2019; https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMsr1904253

