[4] Comment
Date: Thu 6 Jun 2019
From: Karl Johnson <microcaddis@gmail.com> [edited]

The recent report that more than half of the Ebola deaths in the current outbreak occur outside of the WHO-inspired ETCs provides data that clearly indicates that the campaign is not working, despite the use of a very successful live virus vaccine.

To change this equation, a virology test to measure Ebola antibodies in candidate healthcare personnel is the critical 1st step. Then it is time to close the ETCs that the people of the region clearly do not like, send immune personnel to all local treatment sites, and vaccinate all family members and others who have contacted patients. Only when the residents believe they will get medical attention in sites they generally use will this horrendous epidemic be finally controlled.

--
Karl M Johnson MD
<microcaddis@gmail.com>

[ProMED thanks Karl Johnson for submitting his thoughts on how to turn around the current battle against Ebola in the DRC. Trust Karl Johnson to think outside the box! But the problem I see with this suggestion is the question of whether there are enough immune doctors from the region to work in local treatment centers. There are approximately 110 healthcare personnel who have been infected to date, likely because they were not vaccinated. Are they refusing vaccination, or is the vaccine not reaching them? This would have to be addressed. Alternatively, or in addition, would foreign doctors be accepted in the local centers? I am not sure. It may just bring us back to the same issue of distrust of outsiders by the locals. But I think it is worth trying, along with working directly with the communities, to change the environment of distrust. - Mod.LK

